00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:59.599
We're creating features that capture fraud patterns.

00:17:00.799 --> 00:17:03.200
These features fall into three categories.

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:06.239
First, time-based features.

00:17:06.239 --> 00:17:10.160
We extract the hour day because late night transactions

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:12.560
between midnight and 5 a.m. are riskier.

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:15.520
We also flag weekend transactions

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:19.760
because fraud patterns differ on weekends versus weekdays.

00:17:21.280 --> 00:17:23.920
Second, amount-based features.

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:27.439
We flag high-value transactions over $5,000.

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:30.880
We calculate transaction velocity.

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:34.400
How many transactions has this customer made

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:35.839
in the last 24 hours?

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:38.560
And we can calculate rolling sums

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:41.040
of transaction amounts over time windows.

00:17:42.079 --> 00:17:43.839
Third, behavioral features.

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:46.640
We calculate z-scores that compare

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:48.160
the current transaction amount

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:50.000
to the customer's typical behavior.

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:52.800
If someone who normally spends $50

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:55.439
suddenly makes a $5,000 purchase,

00:17:55.439 --> 00:17:58.079
that's a high z-score and potentially fraudulent.

00:17:59.439 --> 00:18:02.479
We also encode categorical variables.

00:18:03.119 --> 00:18:05.760
Transaction types are encoded as numbers.

00:18:06.319 --> 00:18:10.079
Debit is zero, credit is one, transfer is two, and so on.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:12.400
We do the same for channels.

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:15.359
Online banking is zero, mobile app one,

00:18:15.359 --> 00:18:18.079
ATM two, branch three, point of sale four.

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:21.599
We also include customer-level features.

00:18:22.072 --> 00:18:27.912
and a production system. We join this with the customer table to get credit scores, account

00:18:27.912 --> 00:18:34.232
tenure, and risk ratings. For this demo, we're using simplified default values, but the structure

00:18:34.232 --> 00:18:41.192
is there for real customer data. Looking at the model training section, we're using XGBoost,

00:18:41.192 --> 00:18:47.592
which is an excellent choice for fraud detection. After training, we evaluate the model on a held

00:18:47.832 --> 00:18:55.592
test set. We calculate several metrics. First, accuracy. What percentage of predictions are

00:18:55.592 --> 00:19:04.552
correct? Second, precision. Of the transactions we flagged as fraudulent, how many are actually

00:19:04.552 --> 00:19:06.792
fraud? Third, recall.

00:19:07.071 --> 00:19:13.471
Of all the actual fraud transactions, how many did we catch? High recall means we're not missing fraud.

00:19:14.191 --> 00:19:23.151
And fourth, the F1 score, the harmonic mean of precision and recall. This gives us a single

00:19:23.151 --> 00:19:28.751
number to optimize. Let me run the script so I can show you the model training in action.

